+  Since quite some bugs have been fixed in WebKit, you might want to detect the 
+  different versions of WebKit browsing your site, and adapt styling and JavaScript to that. 
+  To make this easier for you, we have created a JavaScript library that does just this, 
+  and this page that shows you how to use it.
+</p>
+<p>
+  The library consist of three functions, of which you will use one fo the following two. 
+  These two are <code>isAppleWebKit(minVersion)</code> and <code>getWebKitVersion()</code>.
+</p>
+<p>
+  <strong><code>isAppleWebKit(minVersion)</code></strong><br/>
+  This function returns true or false and can be used in two ways:
+</p>
+<pre>
+if ( isAppleWebKit() )
+  create nice page</pre>
+<p>	
+  Which will return true if the browser is WebKit based. Or:
+</p>
+<pre>
+if ( isAppleWebKit(418) )
+  create page with specific function</pre>
+<p>
+  This way, you can use functions that have been fixed or added in later versions of WebKit, 
+  and still show a nice page to other users.
+</p>
+<p>
+  <strong><code>getWebKitVersion()</code></strong><br/>
+  This will return an array, which you can use like this:
+</p>
+<pre>
+version = getWebKitVersion();
+document.write(version.major + " " + version.minor + " " + version.browser);
